SIMPLE: engagement
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Engagement
<hw>En*gage"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>engagement</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of engaging,
pledging, enlisting, occupying, or entering into contest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being engaged, pledged or occupied;
specif., a pledge to take some one as husband or wife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which engages; engrossing occupation;
employment of the attention; obligation by pledge, promise, or contract;
an enterprise embarked in; <as>as, his <ex>engagements</ex> prevented
his acceptance of any office</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Religion, which is the chief <qex>engagement</qex> of our
league.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>An action; a fight; a
battle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In hot <qex>engagement</qex> with the Moors.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>The state of being in gear;
<as>as, one part of a clutch is brought into <ex>engagement</ex> with
the other part</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Vocation; business; employment; occupation;
promise; stipulation; betrothal; word; battle; combat; fight; contest;
conflict. See <er>Battle</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Engager</ent>⟦br⟧
